component.illusobjdesc:
Of the two, the upper drawing is a more complete picture of a gowned female figure facing right.  The figure kneels with at least the right arm bent upwards; 
            its hands, however, are not visible.  The figure’s head appears in outline, and may be bowed.  The combination of an upward-bent arm and a 
            bowed head may indicate a figure that is praying.  The figure’s feet are prominent beyond the hem of her gown.

The lower right portion of the leaf contains an enlarged sketch of Job's daughter immediately to the right of his left arm in the design above.  Her head is bent downward as she 
                     faces to the left, but with her body facing partly forward.  She is gowned and has her arms crossed over her breast; 
                     the fingers of her right hand are spread apart slightly.

Job's wife, gowned, sits next to her husband.  Her legs face to the left, but her upper body and head are twisted 
                     toward the viewer; 
                     her eyes may be raised upward.  She raises her upward-bent arms above her head with her hands clasped together, perhaps in prayer.  There may be a belt at her waist.
